3369beb4-b3f6-40ef-b13b-e3a8b4e5f3f5.42054e33-3ccd-4b23-bffe-ff775c1dc0bd.prompt=vCenter Username\: 3369beb4-b3f6-40ef-b13b-e3a8b4e5f3f5.4715ab60-eb84-4268-a7b5-e5db24d2a2f6.description=This flow sets the memory size and cpu count for a virtual machine. Inputs\: vCenterHost - VMware host hostname or IP. vCenterUsername - VMware username. vCenterPassword - VMware user's password. vCenterPort - Port to connect on. Examples\: 443, 80 vCenterProtocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: "https", "http" closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation Valid inputs\: true, false virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123). vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid). vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. memorySize - New memory size for the virtual machine in megabytes. This number must be a multiple of 4. cpuCount - New number of CPUs for the virtual machine. waitGuest - If "true" the flow will wait for the virtual machine's guest operating system. Default\: true poolingRetries - The number of checks the flow will do to the guest operating system to check if it's in the expected state. Default\: 10 poolingInterval - The seconds the flow will wait between two checks of the guest operating state. Default\: 10 Responses\: success - The flow completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: returnResult - The flow primary result containing a success message in case of success or the reason of failure in case of failure. Notes\: 1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ . If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive. 2. Memory limits\: The maximum value for 'memorySize' is based on the virtual hardware version of the virtual machine. Limits are as follows\: Virtual hardware 11 (vSphere 6.0)\: 4177920 Virtual hardware 10 (vSphere 5.5)\: 1035264 Virtual hardware 9 (vSphere 5.1)\: 1035264 Virtual hardware 8 (vSphere 5.0)\: 1035264 Virtual hardware 7 (vSphere 4)\: 261120 Virtual hardware 4 (ESX 3.x)\: 65536 Virtual hardware 3 (ESX 2.5)\: 3600 For more details regarding configuration maximums and virtual machine compatibility settings see http\://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-60/index.jsp\#com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-789C3913-1053-4850-A0F0-E29C3D32B6DA.html 3. CPU limits\: The maximum value for 'cpuCount' is based on the virtual hardware version of the virtual machine. Limits are as follows\: Virtual hardware 11 (vSphere 6.0)\: 128 Virtual hardware 10 (vSphere 5.5)\: 64 Virtual hardware 9 (vSphere 5.1)\: 64 Virtual hardware 8 (vSphere 5.0)\: 32 Virtual hardware 7 (vSphere 4)\: 8 Virtual hardware 4 (ESX 3.x)\: 4 Virtual hardware 3 (ESX 2.5)\: 2 For more details regarding configuration maximums and virtual machine compatibility settings see http\://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-60/index.jsp\#com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-789C3913-1053-4850-A0F0-E29C3D32B6DA.html 4. The number of CPUs specified in the 'cpuCount' must not exceed the number of CPUs available on the ESX/ESXi host on which the Virtual Machine will run. When the specified value is greater than the number of CPUs available and below the configuration maximums the number of CPUs will be set to that value for the specified virtual machine however the virtual machine will not be usable. 5. The flow preserves the initial power state of the virtual machine after the customization was applyed. 3369beb4-b3f6-40ef-b13b-e3a8b4e5f3f5.4773f3b7-3734-4832-ab15-f93dee4f7a05.description=This flow starts a virtual machine (power on) and eventually waits for the guest operating system based on "waitGuest" input. Inputs\: vCenterHost - VMware host hostname or IP. vCenterUsername - VMware username. vCenterPassword - VMware user's password. vCenterPort - Port to connect on. Example\: 80, 443 Default\: 443 vCenterProtocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: http, https Default\: 443 closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation. Valid values\: true, false. virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventory path (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123). vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type Valid values\: inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid. vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. If host is ESX(i) use "ha-datacenter". waitGuest - If "true" the flow will wait for the virtual machine's guest operating system, otherwise it will just start the virtual machine. Default\: true poolingRetries - The number of checks the flow will do to the guest operating system to check if it's in the expected state. Default\: 10 poolingInterval - The seconds the flow will wait between two checks of the guest operating state. Default\: 10 Responses\: success - The flow completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: returnResult - The flow primary result containing a success message in case of success or the reason of failure in case of failure. Notes\: 1) Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server, inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ . If host is a vCenter, the inventory path will be\: /vm//. The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive. 3369beb4-b3f6-40ef-b13b-e3a8b4e5f3f5.4cadcaf7-6f64-43ab-99e6-80111aff24b5.prompt=vCenter Username\: 3369beb4-b3f6-40ef-b13b-e3a8b4e5f3f5.645dfea4-4fd2-403c-b0d6-cc02ecf19f22.description=
Deploys a virtual machine from a template. The source is the templateName while the deploy is defined by .

Note\: cannot work across virtual datacenters

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
Default value\: 800
    templateName - Name of the template to deploy from. 
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. If host is ESX(i) use "ha-datacenter".
    vmName - Name of new virtual machine being created.
    vmFolder - Virtual machine's inventory folder. Folder names are delimited by a forward slash "/".  This input is case sensitive.  Only supported when host is a vCenter.  For root folder, use "/".
Example\: /Hewlett Packard Enterprise/Operations Orchestration/VMs
    vmResourcePool - Resource pool for new virtual machine. Resource pool names are delimited by a forward slash "/".  For the root resource pool, specify "Resources" or a single "/".
    dataStore - Name of datastore or datastore cluster to store new virtual machine (eg. host\:dsname, mydatastore).  If not specified the same datastore of the source virtual machine will be used.
    hostSystem - Name of destination host system (ESX or ESXi) for new virtual machine as seen in the vCenter UI.  Only supported when host is a vCenter.  If not specified the same host system of the source virtual machine will be used.
    clusterName - Name of the VMWare HA or DRS cluster.  Can be specified instead of hostSystem if the desired destination ESX(i) host is in a DRS or HA cluster.
    thinProvision - Specifies whether to perform thin provisioning of the virtual disk. If empty, the disk format will be set as same format as source. If true, the disk format will be set as thin provisioned format. If false, the disk format will be set as thick format.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    customizationTemplateName - Name of the customization specification to apply while creating this clone. The customization specification should already exist in the vCenter customization specifications manager. If  both 'customizationTemplateName' and 'customizationSpecXml' have values, the flow will fail.
    customizationSpecXml - The Xml string of the customization spec.
    connectionTimeout -  The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout -  The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes\:
1) The result of the VMware/VMware Virtual Infrastructure and vSphere/Guest/Export Guest Customization Spec operation can be used to get the customizationSpecXml input value.
2) Note that "socketTimeout" and "connectionTimeout" inputs do not represent the time to wait for the operation to complete. They are used when communicating with the service, to make sure that the service is up and responds to client's requests. They can be used for service diagnosis purpose.
3) The "taskTimeOut" input is only used when the task is performed in a synchronous manner ("async" is set to "false").
